<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Sequester Chaos?
</HL>
<DATE>
09/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   Washington just relived a famous scene from an Indiana
Jones movie. Shrouded in black, the bad guy brandished his
scimitar expertly, seemingly poised to do great damage to our
hero. Jones shrugged, pulled out his gun, and shot the
villain down. This is about what happened to stunned Members
of Congress on Tuesday when New Hampshire Sununu pulled out a
copy of the Anti-Deficiency Act.
   The White House Chief of Staff announced that if there is
no budget deal, President Bush is ready to veto any
continuing resolution and go directly to the Gramm-Rudman
budget cuts. There will be no melodramatic apocalyse for the
evening newscasts because Mr. Bush, under his authority in
the Anti-Deficiency Act, can manage the sequester to avoid
chaos.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As we wrote Tuesday, the Anti-Deficiency Act is the law
that says Congress must approve all government expenditures,
but with one huge exception: The President can order
expenditures "in cases of emergency involving the safety of
human life or the protection of property." This gives Mr.
Bush great discretion to keep paying essential government
workers even when Congress fails to write a budget.
   Mr. Sununu took to Capitol Hill a 12-page interpretation
of the Anti-Deficiency Act written by Jimmy Carter's Attorney
General, Benjamin Civiletti, in 1981. The end-is-nigh media
reports warn that Gramm-Rudman would mean havoc in the skies
from fewer air-traffic controllers, a vegetarian diet for
Americans from the furloughing of meat inspectors, the
rending of garments, and the weeping and gnashing of teeth.
Nonsense. As examples of where "life" or "property" are so at
risk that the President can keep people at their jobs, Mr.
Civiletti's memo cited air traffic and meat inspection.
   There is nothing in Gramm-Rudman that limits the
President's emergency powers under the pre-existing
Anti-Deficiency Act. White House budget officials are
probably now reviewing which workers are essential and which
can be sent home. The Reagan administration went through this
drill when it kept essential workers on even after vetoing
continuing resolutions. Military personnel, the FBI and
federal prison guards are clearly necessary to protect life
and property. Congressional staffers most likely come under a
different heading. Some things, of course, cannot be
protected: It's hard to imagine the threat to life or
property from closing down the office that sends out
Congress's franked mail.
   There are some other improvements Mr. Bush could make to
the distribution of cuts under Gramm-Rudman. Education, Labor
and the EPA are among the agencies scheduled for sequester
cuts of less than 5%. Maybe when a budget is eventually
passed these agencies can contribute to a fund to pay air
traffic controllers.
   The Monday deadline for Gramm-Rudman is where
separation-of-powers hits the rubber. "As the law is now
written, the nation must rely initially for the efficient
operation of government on the timely and responsible
functioning of the legislative process," Mr. Civiletti wrote
in his memo. "The Constitution and the Anti-Deficiency Act
itself leave the Executive leeway to perform essential
functions and make the government `workable.'"
   There is fine justice in the prospect of Congress losing
control over the budget because of its recidivist failure to
pass budgets within legal deadlines. Mr. Bush has every right
and even an obligation to use his Anti-Deficiency Act powers
to avoid any mindless sequester. Congress can agree to a
budget that guarantees spending cuts and creates incentives
for economic growth. Or it can watch Mr. Bush solve the
budget deficit on his own.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900927-0091
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900927-0091.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Canadian Senate
   Threatens to Kill
   Value-Added Tax
   ----
   By John Urquhart
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES CANDA S T.SCC G.DAI
</CO>
<IN>
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   OTTAWA -- The Canadian Senate is threatening to defeat the
government's proposed value-added tax, causing alarm in the
business community that has spent millions of dollars
preparing for the new levy.
   Finance Minister Michael Wilson told the House of Commons
yesterday that businessmen are saying there will be "chaos"
if the tax is scrapped.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sears Canada Inc., a Canadian subsidiary of Sears, Roebuck
&amp; Co., said it has ordered 3.5 million copies of its spring
catalog with prices based on the proposed tax taking effect
Jan. 1, as planned by the government. It has also purchased
about 1,000 new cash registers and reprogrammed other
equipment to cope with the levy.
   Coinamatic Group, which operates 70,000 coin-activated
laundry machines, said it has been converting its equipment
to take more quarters to cover the cost of the new tax. But
the company has suspended plans to raise its prices to cover
the cost of the value-added tax, pending the outcome of the
legislative battle, said Richard Adamson, the company's
financial vice president.
   The proposed tax was approved by the House of Commons last
April, but has encountered strong resistance from the
opposition Liberal Party in the Senate, an appointed chamber.
The Liberals hold 52 of the 104 Senate seats.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney said the Liberals are
threatening to undermine Canadian democracy, by frustrating
"the will of the duly elected representatives of the people,"
in the House of Commons.
   To try to get the tax bill through the Senate, he
threatened to use for the first time in Canadian history an
exceptional constitutional power that allows the government
to appoint eight additional senators.
   Such action would require the approval of Queen Elizabeth,
the British monarch who is Canada's titular head of state.
Buckingham Palace officials told the Canadian Broadcasting
Corp. that the Queen would approve the appointment of
additional senators if her approval was requested.
   Businesses, on government instruction, have been
collecting the proposed goods and services tax since Sept. 1
on any transactions that include 1991 business. The National
Arts Centre in Ottawa said that if the tax bill is defeated
it will have to reimburse customers who have paid the tax on
tickets for 1991 productions. "We're waiting like everybody
else to see if the tax is adopted," said box office manager
Robert Cousineau. "It is a bit stressful."
   The new tax, which is to cover most goods and services,
was designed to replace an outmoded 13.5% tax that is applied
at the manufacturers' level on a narrower range of products.
   Manufacturers of some products, including autos, have said
their prices will decline if the tax change occurs. To
encourage car buyers to purchase now instead of waiting for
the proposed tax change, Mercedes-Benz Canada Inc. is
offering a 3.5% price cut until Dec. 31.
   The uncertainty about the tax has been heightened by the
plans of the provinces of Alberta and British Columbia to
fight the proposed tax in the courts. The two provinces claim
the proposed tax is unconstitutional and infringes on
provincial rights. British Columbia also has threatened to
challenge in the court any move by the government to appoint
new government supporters to the Senate to get the tax bill
passed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
