   THE U.S. WILL SELL five million barrels of oil from the
Strategic Petroleum Reserve to rein in surging crude prices.
Bush, who until recently had opposed tapping the supply,
called the draw-down a "test." The administration intends to
consult with Germany and Japan about a coordinated, long-term
use of reserves.
   ---
</LP>
