<HL>
   Giving a Hand:
   Betty Flood Finds Job With No Pay
   Holds Some Rewards All Its Own
   ----
   By John D. Williams
</HL>
<DATE>
09/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<LP>
   {From time to time in this column, The Wall Street Journal
will report on efforts by people in business to help others
in need.}
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   AFTER A 7 A.M.-TO-3:30 P.M. DAY as a telephone-systems
assistant at Public Service Electric &amp; Gas Co., Betty Flood
returns to her Newark, N.J., apartment and starts a second
job. It doesn't pay, the hours are terrible and the noise can
be deafening. The 56-year-old Ms. Flood wouldn't have it any
other way.
   Betty Flood runs her own game room/hang-out for the 254
children of the 540-unit apartment complex in which she
lives. Concerned by the number of children who didn't seem to
have a place to go after school, she started the project on
her own in 1978, using space donated by the building's
landlord. Despite open-heart surgery five years ago, she is
still going strong. "As long as I can keep a child from
roaming the streets, I'll stay right here," says Ms. Flood,
who, with four children and 21 grandchildren of her own, has
experience with growing children.
   To a visitor, Ms. Flood's center (it has no official name)
is a bedlam of TV blare, clicking billiard balls, clunking
hand-hockey pucks and shouts and squeals. But Ms. Flood,
whose own apartment is on the floor above, is in control from
the moment she greets her charges with a "Hi, baby, how ya
doin]" as they are signed in until she jots down their time
out (the center opens at 4:30 p.m. and usually closes by 11
p.m.; those under 13 years of age must go home by 8 p.m.).
   Should a youth become rowdy, Ms. Flood brings the offender
back in line by brandishing a hollow plastic toy baseball
bat. But that's as rough as it gets, and the posted rules --
such as "anyone cursing will be suspended for six weeks" --
are mostly obeyed. "When Betty Flood speaks, the kids
listen," says John Jenkins, principal of a nearby elementary
school. "She has the respect of all the kids in that complex
and they're better children for the experience."
   It's more than just a safe place to go after school. Ms.
Flood leads rap sessions with the youths, whose ages range
from a preschool four to a high school 18, and teaches them a
range of skills from reading to neat dressing to chess
playing. She organizes picnics, sponsored by her utility
employer and held in the complex's outside area, and stages
Easter egg hunts and Halloween parties.
   Neither Ms. Flood nor Charlotte Young, a volunteer
assistant, are paid for their efforts. Ms. Flood doesn't even
have an estimate of the annual costs of running the center,
which is supported by donations from local merchants and
other businesses.
   Fiori DePhillips, owner of the nearby Roseville Pharmacy
which is contributing about $300 to Ms. Flood's Halloween
party, has a high regard for Ms. Flood's work. "She helps
keep the kids off the streets and out of trouble and is
showing us how to get along and work together," he says.
   Although some local politicians have urged her to seek
public funding for her effort, she has declined. "If I took
state, federal or city funds, I would have to take in
children from other areas and I couldn't control them," she
says.
   Meanwhile, she's looking forward to January when her
center will move into a twice-as-large space at the complex
where there will be two bathrooms -- one for boys, one for
girls -- and a full-sized pool table given by Ms. Flood's
employer, PSE&amp;G. She sees no problem filling the new quarters
with active kids.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900927-0046
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900927-0046.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Study by Panel
   On Integrity Tests
   Proves Inconclusive
   ----
   By Gilbert Fuchsberg
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   A long-awaited congressional study failed to resolve
whether written integrity tests can reliably predict
dishonest behavior. The move effectively offered a reprieve
to thousands of employers who want to keep using the
controversial tests.
   The study, by Congress's Office of Technology Assessment,
questioned the credibility of research supporting the tests
but didn't dismiss it. The result: a declaration that
available evidence isn't conclusive.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Because it isn't overtly negative, the finding deprives
foes of the exams of ammunition and appears to lessen the
potential for an outright ban. Integrity test makers have
lobbied for months against an unfavorable finding, fearing
federal limits comparable to those passed two years ago
against most lie-detector tests.
   While hedging on the validity issue, the report urged
"further government attention" to concerns arising from
intrusive test questions, a lack of safeguards against the
misuse of test results and the fact that many honest people
are rejected from jobs because they fail the exams. The
report also urged further study to insure that the tests
don't discriminate against minorities and women.
   "Assuming even a modest error rate, widespread use of
integrity tests could deny opportunity to many individuals,"
the study said. It cited data showing that the number of
people "incorrectly identified" as dishonest on some tests
range as high as 97%.
   Such findings drew praise from the National Employment
Lawyers Association, a workers' rights group, which said
integrity tests should be banned because they can "smear
honest job applicants."
   But a group of the largest publishers of the tests, who
maintain that the exams are more effective than alternative
screening methods, assailed the study as "inaccurate and
without scientific merit." They termed supportive comments
from some experts in the report as "positive aspects," but
repeated previously reported assertions that the technology
office distorted data to bolster an anti-testing bias.
   Officials of the office have denied the charges but may
face close scrutiny when lawmakers hold hearings on the issue
early next year. Legislative proposals to protect the
privacy, legal rights and job chances of people who take the
tests are probable, congressional aides said. They wouldn't
rule out efforts to ban the tests but judged them less
likely, given the intensity of the publishers' efforts as
well as complex and conflicting evidence about whether the
tests work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900927-0045
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900927-0045.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- U.S. Trust Corp.:
   Pretax Charges Will Cause
   $7 Million Loss in Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
09/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   USTC IBM
</CO>
<IN>
EASTERN U.S. BANKS (BAE)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   U.S. Trust Corp. said it expects to report a third-quarter
loss of about $7 million, or 77 cents a share, because of $25
million in pretax charges against earnings in the quarter.
   However, the New York banking company, which specializes
in asset management and private banking, said it expects
fourth-quarter net income to exceed the $4.4 million, or 44
cents a share, earned in the year-earlier quarter.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   H. Marshall Schwarz, chairman and chief executive officer,
said the special charges will improve operating results and
significantly strengthen asset quality and loan-loss
reserves. "Our capital position remains exceptionally strong
and our dividend-paying ability is unimpaired."
   The charges include $17.4 million associated with its
wholly owned software subsidiary, Financial Technologies
International, and $7.6 million associated with commercial
real estate loans remaining in its corporate loan portfolio.
U.S. Trust has been liquidating the portfolio since 1987.
   Separately, U.S. Trust said it agreed with International
Business Machines Corp. to form a joint venture to design and
market trust and global custody systems for financial
institutions. U.S. Trust will contribute its Financial
Technologies International business and personnel, while IBM
will provide initial funding for anticipated developmental
projects. Financial details weren't disclosed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
