<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Bush Expected to Ask Congress to Clear
   $7.5 Billion Arms Sale to Saudi Arabia
   ----
   By Walter S. Mossberg
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST EUROP FORGN UTX
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
PETROLEUM (PET)
BANKS (BNK)
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- President Bush is expected to ask Congress
to approve an immediate $7.5 billion arms sale to Saudi
Arabia, administration officials said.
   The sale, expected to include modern tanks, armored
personnel carriers and anti-tank missiles, would be the first
portion of a package of over $20 billion publicly debated
here in recent days.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Originally, the administration hoped to submit the entire
package -- including items with a longer delivery time, such
as jet fighters. But supporters of Israel complained that the
huge sale might endanger that nation, so the administration
has decided to seek urgent items now and defer the rest until
early next year.
   Meanwhile, Turkey's President Turgut Ozal said his nation
would support "armed intervention" against Iraq if it becomes
necessary, provided the action is approved by the United
Nations.
   At a breakfast here with reporters, Mr. Ozal was asked
whether Turkey would remain neutral in any war by the U.S.
and its allies against Iraq. He said military force should be
considered only if the economic embargo fails. But he added:
"If the United Nations decides on the armed intervention, we
will not be against it." He contrasted that stand with
Turkey's neutrality in the Iran-Iraq war.
   Mr. Ozal's comment was the second in two days by a major
power hinting that a U.N.-sanctioned military strike against
Iraq would be supported if the embargo fails. On Tuesday,
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze warned Baghdad
that the U.N. has the power to "suppress acts of aggression"
through force.
   Separately, Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney said the
Persian Gulf crisis may be entering a period of "danger" in
which Saddam Hussein "may seek to use his military force to
try to break the stranglehold that the embargo has imposed."
   He said the administration is determined "to see to it
that we send enough forces over there so that we don't leave
them exposed and at the end of a long supply line and
increase the risk to any higher level than is warranted." He
asserted, "The president believes in what I describe as the
`don't screw around' school of military strategy."
   And Secretary of State James Baker disclosed that Iraq has
demanded from the U.S. and other nations a list of
nondiplomats being sheltered in their embassies in Baghdad.
Mr. Baker said Iraq has threatened to execute Americans and
others who hide such people, adding: "We've received a note
to that effect. It falls under the heading of the principle
of the three R's, I think -- we've read it, it's repugnant
and we reject it."
   The latest phase of the economic embargo against Iraq,
which covers air traffic, got off to a confused start. Jordan
continued to receive Iraqi passenger flights. The State
Department said flights involving only passengers might not
be covered by the embargo but should be barred by an earlier
U.N. ban on financial transactions with Iraq. Jordan said it
was reviewing the passenger flights, and U.S. officials said
the U.N. might have to clarify the passenger-flight issue.
Mr. Cheney said the U.S. military hasn't been asked to
enforce the air embargo and he doesn't expect that it will do
so.
   Also, Kuwait's minister of oil and finance, Sheik Ali
Khalifa al-Sabah, said he believes little more can be done to
pressure Iraq short of using military force. "It's time
either for Iraq to bend to the will of the world or be faced
with the military option," he said.
   But Mr. Ozal stressed that the use of force isn't imminent
and that the world should wait at least three or four months
to see if the embargo can force Iraq to withdraw from Kuwait.
He said the U.S. hadn't asked Turkey to join in a military
strike and added: "I don't want to speculate more about it."
   A Turkish role in any military action would be crucial as
Turkey borders Iraq and has a powerful army trained by the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization. Mr. Ozal said "Turkey is
on the side of the Western world in this problem."
   The U.S. Export-Import Bank is expected today to clear a
$1.37 billion loan guarantee to help Turkey purchase 200
military-type helicopters. The helicopters would come from
the Sikorsky Aircraft Division of United Technologies Corp.,
Hartford, Conn., or other U.S. suppliers. The loan guarantee,
which would be the largest single financial transaction in
the history of the U.S. export credit agency, was tentatively
cleared earlier, and Ex-Im Bank officials said the bank's
board now could give it final approval because the House and
Senate Banking committees haven't raised any objections
during a mandatory 25-day review period.
   Mr. Ozal, who met with President Bush Tuesday, said he
doubts Iraqi President Saddam Hussein will be overthrown in a
coup because of his control over Iraqi society. But he added
that he thought the Iraqi leader would be ousted if he is
forced to give up Kuwait. Because of that, he said,
withdrawal will be "very difficult" for Saddam Hussein.
   Nevertheless, Mr. Ozal said, Iraq can be forced to move,
and the embargo might work. He said it is worth trying
because it is unprecedented in history.
   Mr. Ozal said the Kuwaiti rulers might lack popular
support in their own nation if a referendum were held. But he
said it would be a "grave mistake" to offer any concessions
to Iraq in return for a pullout from Kuwait as that would
encourage aggression by others and turn the "new world order"
into a "jungle."
   The Turkish leader said his nation is suffering
economically from the crisis and hasn't yet received promised
compensation. But he stressed that the financial plight of
Turkey has been "exaggerated" in the press, causing a few
banks to be unwilling to roll over short-term export
financing. He said Turkey would survive the crisis
economically and shouldn't be lumped together with much
poorer states as Egypt and Jordan.
   Meanwhile, the Treasury issued licensing regulations for
the export of donated food to Iraq and Kuwait. The department
said it will grant export licenses for food shipments "to
relieve human suffering" on a case-by-case basis but only
after the U.N. has approved each donation. It said such aid
must be provided by humanitarian agencies under U.N.
auspices.
   So far, the Treasury has had only two inquiries about food
licenses, said Richard Newcomb, director of the office of
foreign assets control.
   ---
   John T. Norman contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900927-0028
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900927-0028.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   S&amp;L Regulators Tell Neil Bush Hearing
   Certain Thrift Regulations Are Vague
   ----
   By Paul Duke Jr.
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   F
</CO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   DENVER -- Federal regulators conceded that some of the
conflict-of-interest regulations Neil Bush allegedly violated
as a director of a Denver thrift are vague and don't
explicitly forbid the business relationships he had with
borrowers.
   The comments came in testimony during a hearing on
administrative charges brought against Mr. Bush, the
president's son, by the Office of Thrift Supervision. The OTS
has charged Mr. Bush with violating regulations by not fully
disclosing to fellow board members the extent of his business
ties with two real estate developers. Those developers were
involved in at least $130 million in loans and other
transactions at Silverado Banking, Savings &amp; Loan Association
and caused losses of at least $60 million to the thrift.
Silverado collapsed in December 1988 and is expected to cost
taxpayers $1 billion to clean up.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   However, in a development that may prove damaging to Mr.
Bush's defense, the administrative law judge overseeing the
hearings said the written record showed that the involvement
of a company run by Mr. Bush with a company run by developer
Kenneth Good wasn't disclosed when Mr. Bush sought a $900,000
line of credit for Mr. Good. In 1986, Mr. Bush set up JNB
International Inc. to participate in a consortium with Good
International Inc. to seek oil and gas business in Argentina.
Mr. Bush sought the line of credit from Silverado so that
Good International could prove its financial strength to the
Argentinian government.
   But minutes of Silverado board meetings and a memo
prepared for Silverado management indicate the board was told
only that Mr. Bush's other oil company, JNB Exploration Inc.,
had an affiliation with Good International. The involvement
of JNB International "certainly was not disclosed on any of
these forms," the law judge, Daniel Davidson, said during the
proceedings. The OTS has specifically charged Mr. Bush with
making an "insufficient" disclosure because of the
involvement of JNB International.
   Mr. Bush has said that he told Silverado officials orally
of the connection with JNB International and that the mention
of JNB Exploration in the documents made it clear he and Mr.
Good were involved in the venture. But a former regulator
hired by Mr. Bush as an expert witness admitted it may have
been important for the board to know exactly which entity was
involved in the transaction. For instance, he said, the board
might be interested to know whether Mr. Bush had different
levels of personal liability in the companies.
   Though the OTS officials said the regulations governing
conflict of interest weren't explicit, the agency has
maintained it has broad power to challenge the conduct of
directors and officers for breaches of fiduciary duty or for
unsafe and unsound practices. It wasn't clear whether the
concessions by regulators yesterday would hurt the
government's case.
   Under questioning by James Nesland, an attorney for Mr.
Bush, federal officials who regulated Silverado insisted that
Mr. Bush breached his duty to the thrift, but admitted that
regulations don't specifically list the kinds of business
relationships that constitute a conflict of interest.
   In one of the three charges against Mr. Bush, the OTS said
he shouldn't have voted on $100 million in loans and other
transactions involving real estate developer Bill Walters
because Mr. Walters had an investment in JNB Exploration, and
had given Mr. Bush's company a $1.8 million line of credit
from a bank controlled by Mr. Walters. Mr. Bush didn't
disclose these ties on conflict-of-interest forms he filled
out at Silverado.
   But Terry Sandefur, a former regulator of Silverado now
with the OTS in Topeka, Kan., admitted that the regulations
don't explicitly say a director is forbidden from voting on
loans in such a situation. Mr. Nesland needled Mr. Sandefur
about his testimony that such business connections could lead
a director to act against the interests of the thrift, even
if only "subconsciously."
   "Does a director have to discern his subconscious?" Mr.
Nesland asked.
   "No, but a director has to use reasonable standards," Mr.
Sandefur replied.
   Yesterday was the second day of the hearings at the
federal court house here. Mr. Bush again didn't attend, but
is expected to testify today, along with another former
director.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
