<HL>
   Business Brief -- Avery Inc.:
   Merger Accord Completed
   With Holders, Top Officers
</HL>
<DATE>
09/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   AVRY
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
COAL PRODUCERS (COA)
</IN>
<LP>
   Avery Inc. said it completed a merger agreement with its
two controlling shareholders and top officers under which
they will acquire the shares they don't already own for about
$4 million.
   The two are Nelson Peltz and Peter May, who own 83% of
Avery. Avery said the two will acquire the remaining 9.5
million shares at 43 cents a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Avery said its directors approved the merger agreement
following the recommendation of a special committee appointed
to evaluate the proposal.
   In over-the-counter trading, Avery shares were quoted
yesterday at a bid price of 31 cents a share.
   Avery started out as a coal company in 1984. In 1986, it
bought Uniroyal Chemical Holding Co. from Uniroyal Inc. for
$710 million and financed the acquisition through $910
million of high-yield, high-risk junk bonds. It then sold
Uniroyal Chemical to a management-led group last year in a
transaction valued at $800 million.
   Avery, which continues to operate a coal company, said
last November that after fees and repayment of debt the
company was left with about $24 million in cash and
securities from the Uniroyal sale.
   When the company completed the sale of Uniroyal Chemical
last year it also completed a recapitalization in which
Messrs. Peltz and May surrendered warrants and preferred
stock in exchange for a larger stake in Avery's common
shares.
</TEXT>
